VOCABULARY

Hey there! Just checking in.

Hey there, got a minute?

Catch you later!

Talk soon!

Have a good one!

We use "Hey there! Just checking in." in informal situations and
it's an example of using informal grammar.

Omitting words in informal grammar
In informal situations, we often leave out the subject 
("I", "you" or "we") and the auxiliary verb ("have", "will", "be", "do").

This makes the sentence shorter and more casual.

I'm just checking in.
formal or neutral, using a subject and auxiliary verb

Just checking in.
informal, no subject or auxiliary verb

Catch you later!
It's a casual version of "I'll see you later".

It was great to hear from you. (We'll) Talk soon!
In a casual situation, we usually omit 
the subject "I" or "we" when it's clear from the context.

Hey there, got a minute?
It's a casual version of "Have you got a minute?"

(Do you) Want a coffee?

...) Got a moment to discuss this?(Have you)
(...) Feeling better today?(Are you)

to delete
If you delete a message, you canâ€™t get it back.

She says she accidentally deleted the message.

I always delete unnecessary messages.

to reply
Please reply to my text so I know you got it.

After reading the message, I replied right away.
I like to reply quickly to my friends' messages.

to type
She types very quickly when she sends texts.

You didn't type the word correctly. There's a spelling mistake.

"I need to type a quick message to my friend."
"Go ahead, Iâ€™ll wait."

"I accidentally deleted the entire conversation."
"Oh no! Do you need me to send it again?"

to receive
She received a text while we were talking.

She forwarded me the picture of the sunset you sent.

Did you receive my text about the meeting?

I received a nice message from my mum and replied with a heart emoji.

to forward
She forwarded me the text she got from her boss.

I'm going to forward that funny video to our group chat.

She received a funny video from her cousin.

Give me a call!
Give me a call if you need anything.
She says "Give me a call!" and it's an informal way of saying "Call me."

Give me a call if you have any questions.

Hit me up when you have a second.
Hit me up for dinner this week.
In the phrase "Hit me up!", we use the word 
"hit" to mean "to contact", not "to physically harm".

Hit me up if you're interested in collaborating.
The phrase "Hit me up!" is an informal way of saying "Contact me".

Ping me when youâ€™re free to talk.
Listen Bruno, ping me if you need help with that project, ok?
In the phrase "Ping me!", "to ping" means 
contacting someone electronically via messaging or email.

Ping me if you hear back from the client.

Give me a call! a phone conversation
Ping me! a message via email, text, chat apps

Reach out anytime!
Hi Linda! Reach out when youâ€™re free for a coffee.
We use the phrase "Reach out!" 
if we want somebody to communicate with us.

Reach out to plan our next hiking trip.

Reach......out anytime!
Ping......me anytime!
Hit......me up anytime!

