a tenant á€¡á€­á€™á€ºá€„á€¾á€¬á€¸

A new tenant moved into the building last week.

I'm a tenant in this flat with two other flatmates.

The word "tenant" refers to a person 
who pays rent to live or work in a property.

Each tenant has a key to the main door.

a landlord / a landlady
The landlord collects rent on the first of each month.

I called the landlord to fix the broken window.
The word "landlord" (man) or "landlady" (woman) 
is someone who owns and rents out property.

My landlady explained the rules for the building.

an estate agent
The estate agent helped us find a nice apartment near the city centre.
I work as an estate agent.

The term "(real) estate agent" means a person who helps people buy, sell or rent properties.

I asked the estate agent to show me houses with big gardens.
In the term "estate agent," the word "estate" refers to "property"; "state" can mean "nation".

a tenancy agreement
You need a tenancy agreement to rent a flat legally.
I signed the tenancy agreement last week.
The landlord gave me a copy of the tenancy agreement.

Regional differences
In the context of renting an apartment, some words are different in British and American English.

UK English ðŸ‡¬ðŸ‡§
a flat (a flat)
a tenant (a tenant)
an estate agent (an estate agent)
a tenancy agreement (a tenancy agreement)

US English ðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¸
an apartment
a renter
a realtor
a lease agreement

We hired a realtor to help us find our first home in the city.
I just signed the lease agreement for my new apartment.

In her lease (lease), renters (renters) cut the grass.
The man says his landlord (landlord) does it.

VOCABULARY
a tenant
a landlord / a landlady
an estate agent
a tenancy agreement


Understanding rental terms
Learn compound nouns found in rental contracts

property details
The property details include the size and location of the house.
Before I rented my current flat, I checked the property details carefully.
The website has all the property details for each home available to rent.

Correct or suitable = "proper"; something that you own,
 like land or a building = "property".

a security deposit
Many landlords ask for a security deposit before a tenant moves into an apartment.
I paid a security deposit of $700 before moving in.

The term "security deposit" means the money a tenant gives 
a landlord to pay for any damage.

I have to ask the landlord when I'll get the security deposit back.
Money for potential damage = security deposit, 
a box for keeping valuable items = safety deposit.

tenancy terms
Some tenancy terms may include rules about pets or noise.
I discussed the tenancy terms with the landlady to avoid any problems.


The term "tenancy terms" refers to the rules 
in a rental agreement between a landlord and a tenant.

I asked the landlady to explain the tenancy terms again 
because I was unsure about the rules.

tenancy terms - the rules in a rental agreement
property details - information about a flat's size, location etc.
security deposits - money for potential damage

a utility bill
Utility bills cover the cost of electricity, water and gas.
My utility bills were very high last winter.
I need to pay my utility bills by the end of the month.

The term "utility bill" means a bill for services 
like electricity, water, and rubbish collection.

Compound nouns
In a compound noun, the first noun usually specifies or 
describes the second noun, often by showing its purpose,
 function or origin.

The first noun in a compound noun is usually singular.

utility bills
bills for utilities (water, electricity)

property details
details of a property (house, land)

tenancy terms
terms of a tenancy agreement

The landlord described the property details during the viewing.
Before paying a security deposit, read the rental agreement carefully.

The tenancy terms state that the tenant pays the utility bill.

VOCABULARY
property details
a security deposit
tenancy terms
a utility bill


My landlord must fix important things such as heating.
We use the verb "must" to express obligation.

Differences in meaning

The verbs "need to", "have to", "must" and "shall" express obligation,
 but there are differences in how strong the obligation is.

informal / neutral
need to: rules that feel important
have to: obligation due to rules or laws

Tone of obligation
soft
strong

formal / legal
must: legal or morally important rules
shall: legal obligation

Tone of obligation
very strong
very strong

As a landlord, I must provide a safe property for my tenants.
The speaker thinks he has a legal and moral obligation
 to provide a safe property for the tenant.

As a landlady, I need to make sure my tenants are comfortable.

The tenant shall maintain the property in good condition.
legal context

You have to keep the property in good condition.
everyday conversation

Differences in form
Notice the "to" after the verb in "need to" and "have to".
The verbs "must" and "shall" take the infinitive form of the verb without "to".

have to / need to
They need to / have to sign the agreement.

shall / must 
They shall /must sign the agreem

The tenant has to cover utility bills if they are not included in the rent.
The contract says the tenant shall pay rent on time each month.
The renter must notify the landlord immediately about any problems with the property.

The tenant needs to pay the security deposit before moving in.
We use "need to"+ infinitive to express a necessary rule.
The landlord shall provide the tenant with a copy of the tenancy terms.

The renter needs to avoid making loud noises during early morning hours.

----

Expressing rights and obligations
Learn phrases to talk about rights and obligations

to be allowed to
Tenants are allowed to use the shared garden.
I'm allowed to keep pets in the flat.

Tenants are allowed to use the buildingâ€™s gym as part of their lease.
We use "be allowed" + "to" + infinitive to talk about permissions.

Tenants are not allowed to paint the walls a different colour.

to have the right to
Tenants have the right to privacy in their home.
I have the right to know when my tenacy finishes.
The speaker thinks his landlord must tell him when his tenancy finishes.

I have the right to receive a copy of the contract.

The phrase "to have the right to" means we can do something, 
usually because of a rule or law.

Renters have...
the right to contact the landlord any time.
Tenants are...
allowed to hang pictures on the walls.

to agree to
The tenant agreed to pay for utilities separately from the rent.

I agreed to all the terms in the tenancy agreement.

The speaker accepted all the terms in the tenancy agreement.

The landlord agreed to repair the heating system.

to be required to
Tenants are required to keep the flat clean and undamaged.
We are required to pay a security deposit.

We use the phrase "to be required to" to say we must do something
because of rules or laws.

My landlord is required to keep the property in good condition.
Landlords are required to install smoke alarms in the property.

He says: I was required to leave the flat clean, 
I agreed to general cleanliness, I had the right to get my deposit.

Tenants are allowed to decorate the flat.
It's optional.
Tenants are required to decorate the flat.
It's obligatory.

VOCABULARY
to be allowed to

to have the right to

to agree to

to be required to

Understanding a tenancy agreement
Read an extract from a tenancy agreement

Tenancy agreement

1. ______
This agreement is made between the Landlord, Jonathan Zafar,
 and the Tenant, Sarah Johnson.


2. ______
The rental property is located at 123 Maple Street,
 Apartment 4B, Springfield. It includes two bedrooms, one bathroom,
 a furnished kitchen, and access to a shared garden.


3. ______
The Tenant is required to pay $1,000 before moving in. 
The Landlord shall use it for damages or unpaid rent. 
The money must be refunded within 30 days if the property is in good condition

1. ______Contracting parties
2. ______Property details
3. ______Security deposit

The property details include information about the location
and extras such as a communal garden.

The money must be refunded within 30 days if the property is in good condition.

4. ______

The Tenant is required to keep the home clean and take care of it properly.

The Tenant must inform the Landlord if something is broken or needs repair.

The Tenant agrees to get the Landlordâ€™s permission before making big changes, like painting walls.

5. ______

The Tenant has the right to request repairs 
for any major problems, such as 
broken heating or water leaks, and the Landlord must provide solutions.

The Tenant has the right to privacy. 
The Landlord is not allowed to enter 
the property without permission, except in emergencies.

The Tenant has the right to receive 
a written notice if the rent is going to increase.

